---
import DocsLayout from '../../layouts/DocsLayout.astro';
import StepList from '../../components/StepList.astro';
---

<DocsLayout title="How this works" description="You direct. AI builds. You verify. The AI-First Development Framework explained.">
  <h1 class="mb-6">How This Works</h1>
  <p class="text-text-secondary mb-4">You're going to build real software — websites, apps, APIs, databases — by directing AI to do it. You'll learn to read, inspect, and challenge the code AI produces, without needing to write it yourself.</p>
  <p class="text-text-secondary mb-8">This isn't a trick. It's a methodology. The same one professional teams are adopting right now.</p>

  <!-- The Roles -->
  <h2 class="mb-6 mt-12">The Roles</h2>
  <div class="grid gap-4 sm:grid-cols-3 mb-8">
    <div class="border border-border rounded-lg p-6 text-center">
      <div class="w-14 h-14 rounded-full bg-primary-bg text-primary font-bold text-2xl flex items-center justify-center mx-auto mb-3">D</div>
      <h3 class="text-base font-semibold mb-2">You — the Director</h3>
      <p class="text-sm text-text-secondary">Decide what gets built, review the work, verify it's correct, sign off on every change. Nothing ships without your approval.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="border border-border rounded-lg p-6 text-center">
      <div class="w-14 h-14 rounded-full bg-primary-bg text-primary font-bold text-2xl flex items-center justify-center mx-auto mb-3">C</div>
      <h3 class="text-base font-semibold mb-2">Claude Code — AI Developer</h3>
      <p class="text-sm text-text-secondary">Writes code, creates files, runs tests, opens pull requests. Fast and capable, but makes mistakes. Your job is to catch them.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="border border-border rounded-lg p-6 text-center">
      <div class="w-14 h-14 rounded-full bg-primary-bg text-primary font-bold text-2xl flex items-center justify-center mx-auto mb-3">G</div>
      <h3 class="text-base font-semibold mb-2">Gemini — AI Reviewer</h3>
      <p class="text-sm text-text-secondary">Independently reviews every pull request for security issues and best practices. A second pair of eyes that hasn't seen the code before.</p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- The Loop -->
  <h2 class="mb-4 mt-12">The Loop</h2>
  <p class="text-text-secondary mb-6">Every project follows the same cycle. You'll do this dozens of times until it's muscle memory.</p>

  <StepList steps={[
    {
      title: "Plan",
      content: "You give AI a client brief and a template. AI produces a PRD. You review it: did it add features the client didn't ask for? Are the acceptance criteria specific enough to test?"
    },
    {
      title: "Architect",
      content: "AI produces the technical design: database schema, API contracts, ticket backlog. You review: is it over-engineered? Are the tickets small enough?"
    },
    {
      title: "Build (ticket by ticket)",
      content: "For each ticket: Claude creates a branch, implements, commits, opens a PR. Claude and Gemini both review. You verify and decide: merge it, or direct a fix."
    },
    {
      title: "Deploy",
      content: "The product goes live at a real URL. You verify it works in production, not just on your laptop."
    },
    {
      title: "Reflect",
      content: "Sprint retro: what went well? What did AI get wrong? What acceptance criteria were missing? Lessons get written into the project memory file."
    }
  ]} />

  <!-- What You Actually Do -->
  <h2 class="mb-4 mt-12">What you actually do</h2>
  <p class="text-text-secondary mb-6">You don't write code. But you're not passive. Here's what takes skill:</p>

  <div class="space-y-4 mb-8">
    <div class="border-l-4 border-l-primary bg-primary-bg p-4 rounded-r-lg">
      <p class="font-semibold text-sm mb-1">Planning</p>
      <p class="text-sm text-text-secondary">AI will produce a PRD that looks complete. Your job is to catch scope creep, vague requirements ("should be user-friendly"), and missing edge cases.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="border-l-4 border-l-primary bg-primary-bg p-4 rounded-r-lg">
      <p class="font-semibold text-sm mb-1">Reviewing</p>
      <p class="text-sm text-text-secondary">Every PR gets two AI reviews. You read both. You decide whether the findings matter. You develop judgment about real issues vs false positives.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="border-l-4 border-l-primary bg-primary-bg p-4 rounded-r-lg">
      <p class="font-semibold text-sm mb-1">Verifying</p>
      <p class="text-sm text-text-secondary">You open the product and test it like a real user. Does the form reject bad input? Does the payment charge the right amount? You try to break it.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="border-l-4 border-l-primary bg-primary-bg p-4 rounded-r-lg">
      <p class="font-semibold text-sm mb-1">Communicating</p>
      <p class="text-sm text-text-secondary">You explain technical decisions to non-technical clients. You directed the work, you understand what was built, you communicate it clearly.</p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- Templates -->
  <h2 class="mb-4 mt-12">The Templates</h2>
  <p class="text-text-secondary mb-4">Templates are structured prompts you give to AI. They constrain AI's output so it produces what you need, not what it assumes.</p>
  <ul class="list-disc list-inside text-text-secondary space-y-2 mb-4 text-sm">
    <li><strong class="text-text">PRD template</strong> — turns a client brief into a structured requirements document</li>
    <li><strong class="text-text">Architecture template</strong> — turns a PRD into a technical design with schema, API contracts, and tickets</li>
    <li><strong class="text-text">CLAUDE.md template</strong> — creates the project memory file that keeps AI consistent across sessions</li>
    <li><strong class="text-text">Sprint retro template</strong> — structures the reflection that improves your next project</li>
  </ul>
  <p class="text-text-secondary mb-8">You start by using templates as-is. Over time, you adapt them and eventually create your own. <a href="/templates">Browse all templates →</a></p>

  <!-- Why This Works -->
  <h2 class="mb-4 mt-12">Why this works</h2>
  <p class="text-text-secondary mb-4">AI is powerful but unreliable. It will confidently add features you didn't ask for, recommend libraries that don't exist, and produce financial calculations that are close but not exact.</p>
  <p class="text-text-secondary mb-8">The methodology makes AI reliable by adding structure: templates constrain planning, acceptance criteria constrain implementation, dual review catches errors, and the Director verifies everything before it ships. You're learning the skill that makes AI useful — managing output quality.</p>

  <!-- The Progression -->
  <h2 class="mb-4 mt-12">The Progression</h2>
  <p class="text-text-secondary mb-6">Six projects, each repeating the same loop with one new capability:</p>

  <div class="overflow-x-auto mb-6">
    <table class="w-full text-sm border-collapse">
      <thead>
        <tr class="bg-bg-muted">
          <th class="text-left px-4 py-3 font-semibold border-b border-border">Project</th>
          <th class="text-left px-4 py-3 font-semibold border-b border-border">The +1</th>
        </tr>
      </thead>
      <tbody>
        <tr class="border-b border-border">
          <td class="px-4 py-3 font-medium">1. The Static Site</td>
          <td class="px-4 py-3 text-text-secondary">"I can direct AI to build a website and deploy it to a real URL"</td>
        </tr>
        <tr class="border-b border-border bg-bg-subtle">
          <td class="px-4 py-3 font-medium">2. The Dynamic App</td>
          <td class="px-4 py-3 text-text-secondary">"I can build an app with a database, API, Docker, and automated testing"</td>
        </tr>
        <tr class="border-b border-border">
          <td class="px-4 py-3 font-medium">3. The Interactive App</td>
          <td class="px-4 py-3 text-text-secondary">"I can build something people USE — and I planned it myself"</td>
        </tr>
        <tr class="border-b border-border bg-bg-subtle">
          <td class="px-4 py-3 font-medium">4. The Integrated App</td>
          <td class="px-4 py-3 text-text-secondary">"I can integrate external services and catch when AI hallucinates the API"</td>
        </tr>
        <tr class="border-b border-border">
          <td class="px-4 py-3 font-medium">5. The Multi-User App</td>
          <td class="px-4 py-3 text-text-secondary">"I can build a system where different users see different things — and I can break my own permissions"</td>
        </tr>
        <tr class="border-b border-border bg-bg-subtle">
          <td class="px-4 py-3 font-medium">6. The Live System</td>
          <td class="px-4 py-3 text-text-secondary">"I can keep a real system alive, recover it when it breaks, and hand it to someone else to run"</td>
        </tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>
  </div>

  <p class="text-text-secondary">The loop gets faster each time because you've done it before. By Project 6, you've directed AI through a complete product lifecycle.</p>
</DocsLayout>
